### C. State and Local Tax Analysis (Arizona, Nevada, California)

The **Silver Oak Healthcare acquisition** involves skilled nursing facilities in **three states with materially different tax regimes**—**Arizona** (5 facilities), **Nevada** (4 facilities), and **California** (3 facilities). State and local tax costs vary dramatically depending on whether the transaction is structured as an **asset purchase** or **stock purchase**, with **asset purchases triggering $4M-$5M in sales/transaction privilege taxes** that can be negotiated with the seller.

---

#### 1. Arizona Transaction Privilege Tax (TPT)

**Arizona imposes a transaction privilege tax (TPT), not a traditional sales tax**, on the seller's privilege of doing business—although the economic burden typically passes to the buyer through purchase price adjustments.¹²⁷

##### A. TPT Base Rate and Local Surcharges

| Rate Component | Rate | Authority |
|----------------|------|-----------|
| **State TPT base rate (retail classification)** | **5.6%** | A.R.S. § 42-5010(A) [VERIFIED via Arizona Department of Revenue] |
| **County rates** (Maricopa/Pima average) | 0.7%-1.0% | A.R.S. § 42-6106 |
| **City rates** (Phoenix/Tucson average) | 2.3%-2.6% | Local ordinances |
| **Combined blended rate** (Phoenix/Tucson metro) | **8.3%-8.6%** | [Transaction Privilege Tax, Arizona Department of Revenue (2024)](https://azdor.gov/business/transaction-privilege-tax) |

**For this analysis, we use an 8.6% effective TPT rate** for Arizona facilities located in urban areas (Phoenix metro: 2 facilities; Tucson metro: 3 facilities).¹²⁸

##### B. Tangible Personal Property Subject to TPT

Under **A.R.S. § 42-5061 (Retail Classification)**, TPT applies to sales of **tangible personal property**, defined as "personal property which may be seen, weighed, measured, felt or touched or is in any other manner perceptible to the senses."¹²⁹ This includes:

| Asset Class | TPT Treatment | Rationale |
|-------------|---------------|-----------|
| **Real property** (land, buildings) | **EXEMPT** | Not tangible personal property; no TPT under retail classification |
| **Equipment** (beds, wheelchairs, lifts, medical devices) | **TAXABLE @ 8.6%** | Tangible personal property under A.R.S. § 42-5061(A) |
| **Furniture & fixtures** (desks, chairs, tables, carpets) | **TAXABLE @ 8.6%** | Tangible personal property |
| **Vehicles** (ambulances, vans) | **TAXABLE @ 8.6%** | Tangible personal property |
| **Computers & software** (embedded software) | **TAXABLE @ 8.6%** | Tangible personal property if preloaded; exempt if separately licensed |
| **Inventory** (medical supplies, PPE) | **TAXABLE @ 8.6%** | Tangible personal property |

##### C. Healthcare Exemptions (Nonprofit Limitation)

**Nonprofit healthcare organizations** may qualify for TPT exemptions under **A.R.S. § 42-5159(B)(14)** and **Ariz. Admin. Code § R15-5-2362**, but these exemptions require:¹³⁰

1. **IRC § 501(c)(3) tax-exempt status** (confirmed by IRS determination letter)
2. **Arizona Department of Revenue Exemption Letter** (Form 5000HC)
3. **Licensed nonprofit nursing care institution** status under Arizona law

**CRITICAL LIMITATION:** Sunset Senior Living Group, LLC is **NOT a nonprofit organization**—it is a **for-profit entity owned by Golden Gate Capital**. Therefore:

> **Sunset DOES NOT qualify for Arizona healthcare TPT exemptions.** All equipment and tangible personal property transferred in an asset purchase will be **fully subject to 8.6% TPT** with no exemption available.¹³¹

##### D. TPT Cost Calculation for Arizona Facilities

**Assuming allocation of $27M to Class V tangible personal property** (equipment, furniture, fixtures, vehicles) under the purchase price allocation (see Section IV.D), Arizona's **proportionate share** based on facility count (5 of 12 facilities = **41.7%**) would be:

| Calculation Step | Amount |
|------------------|--------|
| **Total Class V assets (all facilities)** | $27M |
| **Arizona allocation** (5 facilities ÷ 12 facilities) | $27M × 41.7% = **$11.25M** |
| **Arizona TPT @ 8.6%** | $11.25M × 8.6% = **$967,500** |

**After-tax cost to Silver Oak (assuming 21% federal deductibility):**
- Gross TPT payment: $967,500
- Federal tax savings: $967,500 × 21% = ($203,175)
- **Net after-tax cost: $764,325**

##### E. TPT Mitigation Strategies

| Strategy | TPT Savings | Implementation | Risk Level |
|----------|-------------|----------------|------------|
| **1. Stock purchase structure (no Section 338(h)(10))** | $967,500 saved | Forego deemed asset sale; no step-up in basis | LOW (eliminates TPT entirely but sacrifices $47.6M NPV tax benefit—not recommended) |
| **2. Negotiate seller TPT reimbursement** | $400K-$600K | Reduce purchase price by 40%-60% of Arizona TPT ($387K-$580K) | LOW (standard M&A practice) |
| **3. Allocate more to real property (less to equipment)** | $86,000 per $1M shifted | Allocate $1M from Class V (equipment) to Class I (real estate) reduces TPT by $86,000 | MEDIUM (must support with appraisals; IRS may challenge under IRC § 1060) |
| **4. Leaseback equipment from seller** | $967,500 saved | Seller retains ownership of equipment; Silver Oak leases post-closing | HIGH (complex; financing implications; IRS recharacterization risk) |

**RECOMMENDED APPROACH:** Negotiate **50% seller reimbursement** ($484K purchase price reduction) as part of the asset purchase agreement, resulting in net Arizona TPT cost to Silver Oak of **$484K** ($280K after-tax).¹³²

